         <abstract>
            <p>The interpretation of the positive cross-sectional relation between industry accounting rates of return and advertising intensity as evidence that advertising creates entry barriers rests on findings that advertising effects are short-lived. This paper argues that these findings have been biased by observations of marginal rather than average advertising depreciation rates. Then, from studies by Comanor and Wilson and Weiss, new evidence is adduced that advertising is in fact a long-lived investment and is unrelated to correctly measured rates of return. The results stand in opposition to the hypothesis of advertising-created entry barriers.</p>
         </abstract>
